190
00:11:12,740 --> 00:11:16,407
narrator: an antique clock can only be repaired by an expert. 

191
00:11:16,409 --> 00:11:19,877
this person would have either apprenticed under a clockmaker 

192
00:11:19,879 --> 00:11:23,748
or studied timekeeping at a horology school.     

193
00:11:23,750 --> 00:11:25,951
in today's digital landscape, 

194
00:11:25,953 --> 00:11:32,624
horologists are becoming a vanishing breed.       

195
00:11:32,626 --> 00:11:36,228
when your grandfather clock is struggling through old age, 

196
00:11:36,230 --> 00:11:40,031
it's time for a visit to the master clockmaker.   

197
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:42,901
first step -- the dial and the mechanism       

198
00:11:42,903 --> 00:11:45,770
are placed on a stand for observation.        

199
00:11:45,772 --> 00:11:49,174
♪♪         

200
00:11:49,176 --> 00:11:53,244
two horologists inspect the clock for worn-down parts. 

201
00:11:53,246 --> 00:11:56,047
the mechanism contains two gear trains --       

202
00:11:56,049 --> 00:11:57,582
one for keeping time,     

203
00:11:57,584 --> 00:11:59,917
and another to regulate the hammer           

204
00:11:59,919 --> 00:12:02,588
that strikes a bell on the hour.          

205
00:12:02,590 --> 00:12:05,057
after the paperwork is completed,         

206
00:12:05,059 --> 00:12:07,726
the clockmaker gets to work.  

207
00:12:07,728 --> 00:12:09,528
he detaches the hands and dial 

208
00:12:09,530 --> 00:12:11,797
to gain access to the gear trains       

209
00:12:11,799 --> 00:12:14,132
and their linked components.  

210
00:12:14,134 --> 00:12:17,268
he removes tiny screws to release the hands.     

211
00:12:17,270 --> 00:12:21,339
then he removes pins that release the dial's four feet, 

212
00:12:21,341 --> 00:12:24,476
located within holes in the front plate.   

213
00:12:24,478 --> 00:12:26,811
an artist restores the dial.  

214
00:12:26,813 --> 00:12:30,415
the clockmaker unscrews the cast-iron bell       

215
00:12:30,417 --> 00:12:33,618
and begins disassembling the assortment of parts,    

216
00:12:33,620 --> 00:12:35,286
starting with the pallets.   

217
00:12:35,288 --> 00:12:39,691
the pallets receive power from the clock's suspended weights 

218
00:12:39,693 --> 00:12:42,294
and connect with the timekeeping gear train,  

219
00:12:42,296 --> 00:12:44,829
which moves the pendulum.   

220
00:12:44,831 --> 00:12:48,033
the shafts of the hour, minute, and second wheels   

221
00:12:48,035 --> 00:12:50,435
converge at the center of the largest wheel      

222
00:12:50,437 --> 00:12:52,971
on the front plate of the mechanism.       

223
00:12:52,973 --> 00:12:56,908
the clockmaker disassembles these and other components.  

224
00:12:56,910 --> 00:13:00,645
he lifts off the front plate to strip down the inner parts. 

225
00:13:00,647 --> 00:13:02,648
the cables suspending the weights          

226
00:13:02,650 --> 00:13:04,449
are made of woven brass.    

227
00:13:04,451 --> 00:13:07,319
the craftsman cleans all the metal parts      

228
00:13:07,321 --> 00:13:09,187
in an ultrasonic machine.   

229
00:13:09,189 --> 00:13:11,322
its high-frequency sound waves 

230
00:13:11,324 --> 00:13:15,527
force the chemical solution  
into all the nooks and crannies.

231
00:13:15,529 --> 00:13:20,832
he rinses the parts and dries them in jeweler's sawdust.   

232
00:13:20,834 --> 00:13:23,935
each part is inspected under a magnifying glass    

233
00:13:23,937 --> 00:13:26,871
to assess their condition.   

234
00:13:26,873 --> 00:13:28,073
if a part is worn,       

235
00:13:28,075 --> 00:13:30,275
the craftsman tries to restore it      

236
00:13:30,277 --> 00:13:32,077
to its original shape.     

237
00:13:32,079 --> 00:13:35,947
if it's too badly worn, he has to make a replacement  

238
00:13:35,949 --> 00:13:39,617
with a computer-guided milling machine.        

239
00:13:39,619 --> 00:13:42,654
the pin at the end of a gear is called a pivot.       

240
00:13:42,656 --> 00:13:46,023
after measuring its diameter with a digital caliper,    

241
00:13:46,025 --> 00:13:49,161
the clockmaker sets the disk of a filing machine      

242
00:13:49,163 --> 00:13:51,696
to its corresponding measurement.          

243
00:13:51,698 --> 00:13:54,366
he places the pivot between the disk        

244
00:13:54,368 --> 00:14:00,772
and a fine-grinding disk, filing away any rough surfaces.

245
00:14:00,774 --> 00:14:03,508
♪♪         

246
00:14:03,510 --> 00:14:09,714
next, the craftsman works on the rear plate,       

247
00:14:09,716 --> 00:14:12,517
hammering in brass sleeves called bushings        

248
00:14:12,519 --> 00:14:14,519
into multiple gear holes.   

249
00:14:14,521 --> 00:14:17,856
he widens the bushing just enough to insert the pivot   

250
00:14:17,858 --> 00:14:21,326
and smooths out the hole.   

251
00:14:21,328 --> 00:14:25,063
he inserts one end of the pivot
in the rear-plate bushing,   

252
00:14:25,065 --> 00:14:27,833
the other end in the front-plate bushing,  

253
00:14:27,835 --> 00:14:31,536
and checks that the gear rotates smoothly.   

254
00:14:31,538 --> 00:14:37,476
he does the same for each pivot hole.      

255
00:14:37,478 --> 00:14:39,611
then, all the parts are cleaned,

256
00:14:39,613 --> 00:14:41,947
and the mechanism is reassembled.        

257
00:14:41,949 --> 00:14:46,017
this gear on the front plate is the hour wheel.       

258
00:14:46,019 --> 00:14:50,689
♪♪         

259
00:14:50,691 --> 00:14:53,358
the clockmaker attaches the hour rack,         

260
00:14:53,360 --> 00:14:55,560
which connects to the gear train.       

261
00:14:55,562 --> 00:14:57,095
this system regulates     

262
00:14:57,097 --> 00:14:59,631
the striking of the bell on the hour.          

263
00:14:59,633 --> 00:15:02,500
once the mechanism is reassembled,        

264
00:15:02,502 --> 00:15:07,906
the horologist attaches the dial
to the front plate.      

265
00:15:07,908 --> 00:15:11,242
the dial of this clock required no restoration.    

266
00:15:11,244 --> 00:15:17,382
even the original steel hands are still in good condition.  

267
00:15:17,384 --> 00:15:22,053
when hands are in bad shape,  
the clockmaker creates replicas.

268
00:15:22,055 --> 00:15:23,388
when hands are missing,    

269
00:15:23,390 --> 00:15:27,659
he makes new ones in the style of the period.  

270
00:15:27,661 --> 00:15:29,460
during the entire reassembly, 

271
00:15:29,462 --> 00:15:31,195
the clockmaker wears gloves  

272
00:15:31,197 --> 00:15:33,932
to protect the steel and brass components      

273
00:15:33,934 --> 00:15:38,336
from the natural oils in his hands.         

274
00:15:38,338 --> 00:15:40,138
restoring an antique clock   

275
00:15:40,140 --> 00:15:44,141
can take several weeks of meticulous work.      

276
00:15:44,143 --> 00:15:45,410
when it's done,        

277
00:15:45,412 --> 00:15:48,413
the clockmaker mounts the clock
back on the stand,       

278
00:15:48,415 --> 00:15:51,616
connecting the weights and pendulum, and runs a test.   

279
00:15:51,618 --> 00:15:54,219
[ bell dinging ]        

280
00:15:54,221 --> 00:15:57,689
the job is complete when the clock keeps time   

281
00:15:57,691 --> 00:16:00,758
and the hammer strikes the bell
to announce the hour.     

282
00:16:00,760 --> 00:16:03,662
[ dinging continues ]     

283
00:16:10,770 --> 00:16:15,507
♪♪         

284
00:16:15,509 --> 00:16:17,242
narrator: cooking over an open flame   

285
00:16:17,244 --> 00:16:19,711
calls for a serious set of tools.    

286
00:16:19,713 --> 00:16:21,780
barbecue utensils are durable 

287
00:16:21,782 --> 00:16:24,181
and designed to withstand the heat.     

288
00:16:24,183 --> 00:16:26,785
built longer than regular kitchen utensils,   

289
00:16:26,787 --> 00:16:28,320
these tools enable the chef  

290
00:16:28,322 --> 00:16:30,788
to keep an arm's distance from the flame,        

291
00:16:30,790 --> 00:16:36,394
making barbecuing a safe and gratifying experience.   

292
00:16:36,396 --> 00:16:40,065
when barbecuing, it's important
to go big on tools.      

293
00:16:40,067 --> 00:16:42,133
these substantial utensils   

294
00:16:42,135 --> 00:16:44,603
will hold up to the intensity of the flame   

295
00:16:44,605 --> 00:16:48,206
while also offering precision and control.     

296
00:16:48,208 --> 00:16:50,275
making barbecue utensils    

297
00:16:50,277 --> 00:16:54,546
starts with a sheet of high-carbon stainless steel.  

298
00:16:54,548 --> 00:17:00,251
a laser cuts out several parts,
creating turner blades.    

299
00:17:00,253 --> 00:17:01,886
turner blades are broad,    

300
00:17:01,888 --> 00:17:04,890
enabling the user to flip burgers and fillets  

301
00:17:04,892 --> 00:17:06,892
without breaking them.     

302
00:17:06,894 --> 00:17:10,962
they also have slots for draining grease and juices.  

303
00:17:10,964 --> 00:17:16,167
a technician extracts the blades from the matrix   

304
00:17:16,169 --> 00:17:23,174
and punches out the pre-cut drainage slots.  

305
00:17:23,176 --> 00:17:25,844
the turner blades are placed on a rack      

306
00:17:25,846 --> 00:17:32,183
which lowers the blades between two coarse rollers.  

307
00:17:32,185 --> 00:17:35,720
an operator applies polishing compound to the rollers.    

308
00:17:35,722 --> 00:17:37,255
as the rollers turn,      

309
00:17:37,257 --> 00:17:41,325
the friction rubs off stamped information from the steel mill

310
00:17:41,327 --> 00:17:44,796
and other blemishes.      

311
00:17:44,798 --> 00:17:50,101
technicians buff the blades to a smooth, matte texture.  

312
00:17:50,103 --> 00:17:53,338
this gives the blades a consistent polished finish. 

313
00:17:53,340 --> 00:17:58,409
♪♪         

314
00:17:58,411 --> 00:18:01,546
next, the blade is clamped to a special carriage     

315
00:18:01,548 --> 00:18:03,815
moving the blade back and forth

316
00:18:03,817 --> 00:18:06,818
as a grinding wheel carves a thin beveled edge.      

317
00:18:06,820 --> 00:18:09,421
the beveled edge will make it easier      

318
00:18:09,423 --> 00:18:13,825
to lift meat off the grill.  

319
00:18:13,827 --> 00:18:17,495
an operator clamps the turner blade in a fixture. 

320
00:18:17,497 --> 00:18:21,833
a hydraulic press bends the neck of the blade.  

321
00:18:21,835 --> 00:18:24,301
high-grade walnut is the material used      

322
00:18:24,303 --> 00:18:26,638
to make the utensil handles.  

323
00:18:26,640 --> 00:18:28,373
it's a hard, durable wood   

324
00:18:28,375 --> 00:18:32,043
with a grain that adds visual interest.        

325
00:18:32,045 --> 00:18:33,578
using a bandsaw,        

326
00:18:33,580 --> 00:18:35,713
the operator carves the walnut block        

327
00:18:35,715 --> 00:18:37,515
into smaller chunks.      

328
00:18:37,517 --> 00:18:40,851
each one will become a handle blank.        

329
00:18:40,853 --> 00:18:43,254
he places the blanks on a conveyer         

330
00:18:43,256 --> 00:18:46,925
that takes them through a spinning cutting head.    

331
00:18:46,927 --> 00:18:50,662
the cutting head carves a taper
into the end of the handle   

332
00:18:50,664 --> 00:18:55,934
that will hold the blade tang. 

333
00:18:55,936 --> 00:18:57,736
to refine the shape,      

334
00:18:57,738 --> 00:19:02,073
a craftsman locks two handle blanks on a revolving table.  

335
00:19:02,075 --> 00:19:04,409
moving the handles against a router        

336
00:19:04,411 --> 00:19:09,213
can make the handles smoother for gripping.         

337
00:19:09,215 --> 00:19:15,353
it's quite a transformation.  

338
00:19:15,355 --> 00:19:19,024
multiple drill heads carve rivet holes on one side. 

339
00:19:19,026 --> 00:19:21,493
the holes have a graduated profile      

340
00:19:21,495 --> 00:19:25,030
to allow the rivets to sit flush to the wood.   

341
00:19:25,032 --> 00:19:27,298
the craftsman drills corresponding holes      

342
00:19:27,300 --> 00:19:29,367
on the other side.       

343
00:19:29,369 --> 00:19:31,969
using a circular saw, he cuts a slot         

344
00:19:31,971 --> 00:19:34,572
for the tang -- or stem -- of the barbecue utensil    

345
00:19:34,574 --> 00:19:38,109
to be inserted         

346
00:19:38,111 --> 00:19:39,844
and drills one last hole    

347
00:19:39,846 --> 00:19:44,115
for a piece of rawhide that will hang up the tool.  

348
00:19:44,117 --> 00:19:47,184
♪♪         

349
00:19:47,186 --> 00:19:49,587
next, the craftsman inserts the tang        

350
00:19:49,589 --> 00:19:51,322
into the slot in the handle  

351
00:19:51,324 --> 00:19:54,592
and slides a post through one of the holes.   

352
00:19:54,594 --> 00:19:55,727
this positions it       

353
00:19:55,729 --> 00:20:02,400
for a female rivet to be installed from the front.   

354
00:20:02,402 --> 00:20:05,603
male rivets are installed on the other side.       

355
00:20:05,605 --> 00:20:07,672
this completes the riveting steps       

356
00:20:07,674 --> 00:20:11,275
and secures the handle to the turner blade.      

357
00:20:11,277 --> 00:20:15,013
♪♪         

358
00:20:15,015 --> 00:20:16,881
using a coarse sanding belt,  

359
00:20:16,883 --> 00:20:19,884
the craftsman smooths the rivets to the wood     

360
00:20:19,886 --> 00:20:27,092
and sands off the metal tang at the protruding sides.    

361
00:20:27,094 --> 00:20:30,762
another technician rubs mineral
oil into the wooden handle   

362
00:20:30,764 --> 00:20:34,032
to give it luster and enhance the grain.     

363
00:20:34,034 --> 00:20:37,168
a mixture of ground corn and mineral spirits      

364
00:20:37,170 --> 00:20:40,571
serves as a gentle abrasive cleaner.   

365
00:20:40,573 --> 00:20:42,706
the technician dries off the blade      

366
00:20:42,708 --> 00:20:46,311
by plunging it into just the ground corn.   

367
00:20:46,313 --> 00:20:48,045
with a compressed air gun,   

368
00:20:48,047 --> 00:20:51,316
she blasts off the corn-cob remnants,     

369
00:20:51,318 --> 00:20:53,651
examines the tool for defects, 

370
00:20:53,653 --> 00:20:58,790
and props up the utensil under an engraving laser.   

371
00:20:58,792 --> 00:21:04,195
the laser etches the company name into the metal.      

372
00:21:04,197 --> 00:21:07,265
this barbecue turner will become part of a set   

373
00:21:07,267 --> 00:21:10,768
which will act as an extension of the chef's hands,      

374
00:21:10,770 --> 00:21:13,604
making it possible to cook over an open flame   

375
00:21:13,606 --> 00:21:15,440
without getting burned.    

